    "collapsible_content_t6QUi4": {
      "type": "collapsible-content",
      "blocks": {
        "collapsible_row_HiiLHn": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "What is Himalayan Bee Pollen?",
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Himalayan bee pollen is a nutrient-dense superfood- it is a collection of wild bees especially from high-altitude meadows in Nepal. The source of this pollen is a diverse kind of wildflowers blooming at exceptionally pure conditions above 3,000 meters. Our bee pollen is ethically harvested in small batches, naturally sun-dried, and remains completely raw and unprocessed.</p>",
            "page": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_qjgdr4": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "What are the key benefits of Raw Bee Pollen?",
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Raw Bee Pollen is a natural food containing vitamins, minerals, amino acids, and enzymes. It is traditionally included in diets as a nutrient-dense food ingredient.</p>",
            "page": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_taFCjT": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "How is Wild Bee Pollen different from Regular Bee Pollen?",
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Wild bee pollen is produced by bees feeding on hundreds of species of wildflowers of the wild, sold raw. The regular ones, however, are from those bees that are usually kept in regulated farming conditions- and are mostly from single-crop sources and may be processed as well.</p>",
            "page": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_VzTKUX": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "How should I take Bee Pollen daily?",
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Bee pollen should be started small, with as small as ¼ teaspoon per day. If well tolerated, this dose can be gradually increased to the standard daily serving size of 1–2 teaspoons. Like honey, you can mix it into your everyday smoothies, yogurt or oatmeal.</p>",
            "page": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_dWjWWM": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Is Bee Pollen safe to consume?",
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Bee pollen is a centuries-old natural food. It is safe for healthy adults as long as it is consumed in moderation as part of a balanced diet. The users need to be quality-conscious- always use unprocessed, additive-free bee pollen from reputable sources.</p>",
            "page": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_i6MWmi": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Who should not take Bee Pollen?",
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Individuals with allergies to bee or pollen, pregnant women, breastfeeding women, individuals taking blood-thinning medications or immunosuppressants shouldn’t take bee pollen. Always take medical advice if you are under any medications.</p>",
            "page": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_MXEwPn": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Why choose Bee Pollen from Nepal?",
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>The high meadows in the Himalayan Nepal region have a clean environment that has not been polluted by industries, pesticides and massive agricultural encroachment. The bees here get to access more than 300 native plant species and more importantly, harvesters here practice ethical harvesting methods.</p>",
            "page": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_3nffCp": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "How can I verify the quality of raw Bee Pollen?",
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Authentic raw bee pollen has a natural color- its shade can be varying, from golden yellow to deep orange and brown, totally depending on the sources of the flowers. It must be slightly sweet and floral, never chemical or fermented. Texture should be slightly soft, not too dry or powdery. Also, look for brands with origin, harvesting and processing transparency.</p>",
            "page": ""
          }
        }
      },
